        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1963-02-11T19:44:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1963-02-11T19:44:00-05:00" n="292"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d292">
                <head>292. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in France</gloss>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d292fn0">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, STR 12-3 <gloss target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss>. Secret;<gloss
                            target="#t_NIACT1">Niact</gloss>. Drafted by Kupinsky (<gloss
                            target="#t_EUR1">EUR</gloss>); cleared by <gloss target="#t_EUR1"
                            >EUR</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_E1">E</gloss>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_TWR1">Tyler</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_KFD1"
                            >Kohler</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_DRH1">Davis</persName>, and
                            <persName corresp="#p_BMG1">Bundy</persName>; and approved by <persName
                            corresp="#p_RD1">Rusk</persName>. Repeated to Rome, London, Paris, and
                        Moscow.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1963-02-11T19:44:00-05:00">February 11, 1963, 7:44 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_TOPOL1">Topol</gloss> 1108. Deliver Ambassador Finletter<note
                        n="1" xml:id="d292fn1">Thomas K. Finletter, U.S. Permanent Representative at
                        the North Atlantic Council.</note> by 9:00 a.m. February 12.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Before US Ambassador to <gloss target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss> left Moscow
                        for consultations in Washington, Sov Foreign Minister <persName
                            corresp="#p_GAA1">Gromyko</persName> made oral statement to him
                        expressing Soviet Governmentʼs concern re alleged US pressure on other
                        countries to prevent deliveries of wide-diameter pipe to <gloss
                            target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss>.<note n="2" xml:id="d292fn2">The Embassy
                            in Moscow transmitted the text of <persName corresp="#p_GAA1"
                                >Gromyko</persName>ʼs statement in telegram 1841, January 26.
                            (Department of State, Central Files, STR 12-3 <gloss target="#t_USSR1"
                                >USSR</gloss>)</note>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GAA1">Gromyko</persName> asked US Ambassador to inform
                        President of US that head of Soviet Government, <persName corresp="#p_KNS1"
                            >Khrushchev</persName>, placed particular emphasis on this problem and
                        hoped US Govt and President would take that into account in considering
                        it.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_USG1">USG</gloss> planning low-key reply to <persName
                            corresp="#p_GAA1">Gromyko</persName> on US Ambassadorʼs return to
                        Moscow, about February 14, in following terms: <list>
                            <label>a)</label>
                            <item>US treats pipe over 19 inches as having military and strategic
                                significance and prohibits its export to <gloss target="#t_USSR1"
                                    >USSR</gloss>. If international situation improves and Western
                                Allies able feel danger to their national security has lessened, US
                                would naturally re-examine its position on pipe exports.</item>
                            <label>b)</label>
                            <item>Determination what constitutes “strategic” goods matter for
                                decision by countries concerned based evaluation national security
                                interests. Recent issue East German military magazine emphasized
                                military and strategic importance to Sov Bloc of Friendship pipeline
                                and compared it to <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss>
                                pipeline.</item>
                            <label>c)</label>
                            <item>
                                <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> countries have been discussing
                                question of strategic significance of pipe and exports of pipeline
                                to <gloss target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss>: If certain <gloss
                                    target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> countries have taken action to
                                restrict such exports, such measures have been undertaken strictly
                                on their own responsibility in light of their judgment of their own
                                security interests.</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Request USDel inform Stikker<note n="3" xml:id="d292fn3">Dirk U.
                                Stikker,<gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> Secretary
                            General.</note> beforehand and <gloss target="#t_NAC1">NAC</gloss> Perm
                        Reps at beginning Defense Data briefing February 12 of <persName
                            corresp="#p_GAA1">Gromyko</persName> approach and nature intended US
                        oral reply.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RD1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Rusk</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
